{"title_page": "Frederick Nebel", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{notability|1=Biographies|date=May 2018}}{{primary sources|date=May 2018}}{{Third-party|date=May 2018}}}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Frederick Lewis Nebel\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = Grimes Hill, Eric Lewis, Lewis Nebel\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1903|11|03|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Staten Island]], [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1967|05|03|1903|11|03}}\n| death_place = [[Laguna Beach, California|Laguna Beach]], [[California]]\n| occupation  = Novelist, short story writer\n| nationality = American\n| period      = \n| genre       = [[Crime fiction]], [[Mystery fiction]], [[Romance fiction]]\n| spouse      = \n| notableworks  = ''Sleepers East'' (1933), ''But Not the End'' (1934), ''Fifty Roads to Town'' (1936)\nSerialized Characters: Jack Cardigan, Donny Donahue, MacBride and Kennedy\n| children    = \n}}\n\n'''Frederick Lewis Nebel''' (November 3, 1903 - May 3, 1967), was an [[United States|American]] author with over 300 works to his credit, best known for his [[hardboiled]] [[detective fiction]].<ref name=\"nolan\">{{cite book | author = Nolan, William F. | title = The Black Mask Boys:Masters in the Hard-Boiled School of Detective Fiction | publisher = Mystery Press | location = New York | year = 1985 | isbn = 978-0-892-96931-9 }}</ref> Nebel was a prolific writer, penning up to five thousand words a day, often keeping five to six serial heroes in action from week to week for [[Pulp magazine|the pulps]]. Nebel also wrote three novels and many of his works were adapted for the screen.<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"imdb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0623862/ \"Frederick Nebel (1903 - 1967),\"] [[IMDb]], retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Staten Island, New York, Nebel dropped out of school at 15 after only one day in high school.<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"penzler1\">{{cite book | editor = Penzler, Otto | title = The Black Lizard Big Book of Black Mask Stories | publisher = Vintage Crime / Black Lizard | location = New York | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-0-307-45543-7 }}</ref> He worked as a dockhand and a valet before moving to Canada where he worked as a farmhand on his great-uncle\u2019s homestead. He enjoyed the wilderness and became a self-taught expert in Canadian history. This expertise helped launch his career writing adventure stories for ''Northwest Stories'', beginning in 1925.<ref name=\"detnovel\">[http://www.detnovel.com/Nebel.html \"Frederick Lewis Nebel (1903-1966),\"] [http://www.detnovel.com/ Detnovel.com], retrieved May 12, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"thrilling\">[http://www.thrillingdetective.com/trivia/nebel \"Frederick Nebel,\"] [http://www.thrillingdetective.com/ The Thrilling Detective Website], retrieved May 12, 2018.</ref> He returned to New York and got a job working as a brakeman on passenger trains and writing in his spare time.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Pulp magazines===\nIn 1926, Nebel sold his first ''[[Black Mask (magazine)|Black Mask]]'' story, \u201cThe Breaks of the Game,\u201d to editor Phil Cody. That same year [[Joseph Shaw (editor)|Joseph Shaw]] took over as editor, and throughout his tenure with the magazine, he mentored Nebel as he published his work.<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"detnovel\"/> Over the next 12 years, Nebel published at a fast pace, writing up to 5000 words a day, while publishing in ''Black Mask'' and numerous other pulp magazines, including ''[[Action Stories]]'', ''Danger Trail'', ''Dime Detective'' and ''Sea Stories''.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\nShaw encouraged his authors to develop series characters, and Nebel created the detective duo of Captain Steve MacBride and newspaper reporter Kennedy of fictional \u201cRichmond City\u201d.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> MacBride was a hardboiled homicide detective while drunken, wisecracking Kennedy provided comic relief.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/><ref name=\"The Black Lizard Big Book of Pulps\">{{cite book | editor = Penzler, Otto | title = The Black Lizard Big Book of Pulps | publisher = Vintage Crime / Black Lizard | location = New York | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-307-28048-0}}</ref> The pair was featured in 36 of Nebel\u2019s stories spanning 8 years.[6] In the 1930s, Nebel sold the rights to MacBride and Kennedy to [[Warner Bros.]], who made nine film adaptations.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/><ref name=\"powell\">{{cite book | editor = Powell, Steven | title = 100 American Crime Writers | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = New York | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-0-230-52537-5 }}</ref> The [[CBS Radio]] series ''Meet MacBride'', beginning in 1936, was also adapted from the series.<ref name=\"penzler1\"/>\n\nNebel created Donny \u201cTough Dick\u201d Donahue at the request of Shaw for a character similar to [[Dashiel Hammett|Dashiel Hammett\u2019s]] [[Sam Spade]].<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"powell\"/> Following the huge success of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (novel)|The Maltese Falcon]]'', Shaw wanted more Spade stories but Hammett, a personal friend of Nebel\u2019s, had quit the pulps for Hollywood.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> Donahue was an ex-cop discharged for not giving into corruption, now working for the Inter-State Detective Agency.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/> From 1930 to 1935, Nebel wrote 15 Donahue stories for ''Black Mask''.<ref name=\"detnovel\"/>\n\nFrom 1931-1937, Nebel wrote nearly 50 stories for ''Dime Detective'' featuring the character Jack Cardigan, a tough, Irish detective working for the Cosmos Detective Agency in [[St. Louis]].<ref name=\"The Black Lizard Big Book of Pulps\"/>\n\nOther series characters created by Nebel include: Bill Gales and Mike McGill for ''Air Stories'', Brinkhaus for ''Detective Fiction Weekly'', Corporate Chet Tyson for ''Northwest Stories'', and The Driftin\u2019 Kid for Lariat.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\nNebel sometimes wrote under the [[pen name]]s Lewis Nebel, Eric Lewis and Grimes Hill,<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"powell\"/> a name derived from Grymes Hill, near where he was born on Staten Island.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n===Novels and screen adaptations===\nIn 1933, [[Little, Brown and Company|Little, Brown]] published Nebel\u2019s first novel, ''Sleepers East'', based on his early experience as a brakeman on passenger trains.<ref name=\"detnovel\"/> The thriller is set entirely on a ten-hour train ride from the Midwest to New York.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]'', while critical of the genre conventions of a story set on a train, praised Nebel for providing \"thrills a-plenty.\" \"Though lacking credibility as to plot, the story has full measure of action, suspense and emotional conflict.\"<ref name=\"nytimes1933\">[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/06/25/105396143.html?pageNumber=42 \"Drama on a Train; SLEEPERS EAST. By Frederick Nobel. 283 pp. Boston: Little, Brown & Co. $2. Latest Works of Fiction,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/06/25/105396143.pdf   Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', June 25, 1933.</ref> The novel was later adapted to the screen as ''[[Sleepers West]]'' (1941).<ref name=\"penzler1\"/> In 1934, he wrote ''But Not the End'', a novel set in Depression-era New York City. The book was praised for its \"brilliant divergences from the standardized patterns of depression era fiction.<ref name=\"nytimes1934\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1934/03/18/archives/the-new-poor-but-not-the-end-by-frederick-nebel-304-pp-boston.html \"The New Poor; BUT NOT THE END. By Frederick Nebel. 304 pp. Boston: Little, Brown & Co. $2.,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1934/03/18/93755675.pdf   Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', March 18, 1934.</ref> In 1936, he wrote the novel ''Fifty Roads to Town''. ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote,\"This is a first rate, virile piece of story-telling. It moves dramatically but in a restrained and effective manner toward its ultimate goal.\"<ref name=\"rossbach\">Mabel L. Rossbach, [https://www.nytimes.com/1936/02/02/archives/in-a-maine-hotel-fifty-roads-to-town-by-frederick-nebel-299-pp.html In a Maine Hotel; FIFTY ROADS TO TOWN. By Frederick Nebel. 299 pp. Boston: Little Brown & Co. $2,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1936/02/02/85231602.pdf   Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', February 2, 1936.</ref> It was adapted into a comedy film of the [[Fifty Roads to Town|same name]] starring [[Don Ameche]] in 1937.<ref name=\"powell\"/>\n\nHis story \u201cThe Bribe\u201d was adapted into the 1949 movie by the [[The Bribe|same name]], starring [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]], [[Ava Gardner]], [[Charles Laughton]], and [[Vincent Price]].<ref name=\"penzler1\"/><ref name=\"brady\">Thomas F. Brady, [https://www.nytimes.com/1948/04/08/archives/taylor-gardner-in-metro-picture-get-leads-in-the-bribe-fbi-story-of.html \"TAYLOR, GARDNER IN METRO PICTURE; Get Leads in 'The Bribe,' FBI Story of War Surplus Sales in Cuba -- Berman Producer,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1948/04/08/96421792.pdf   Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', April 8, 1948.</ref> On Television, his work was adapted for such shows as General Electric Theater and Studio One.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n===Slick magazines===\nAfter selling the film rights to ''Sleepers East'', Nebel hired agent Carl Brandt.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> After 12 years and more than 230 stories, Nebel stopped writing for the detective pulps in 1937 to focus on romance.<ref name=\"detnovel\"/> Under Brandt\u2019s guidance, Nebel began selling to higher-paying slick magazines such as ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[McCall\u2019s]]'', ''[[Redbook]]'', ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'' and ''[[Woman\u2019s Home Companion]]''.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\nIn 1956 he returned to mystery writing biefly, publishing 6 more short stories for ''[[Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"powell\"/> His last story was published in 1962.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nNebel met his wife, Dorothy Blank, in Paris in 1928.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> They married in 1930 and moved to [[St. Louis]], where much of his fiction is set. In 1934, they moved to Connecticut and in 1937 they had a son, Christopher Nebel. Suffering from high blood pressure, Nebel moved to Laguna Beach, California in the late 1950s.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/><ref name=\"powell\"/>  In 1967 Nebel suffered a cerebral hemorrhage and died three days later at age sixty-three.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nebel, Frederick Lewis}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Pulp fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{notability|1=Biographies|date=May 2018}}{{primary sources|date=May 2018}}{{Third-party|date=May 2018}}}}\n\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Frederick Lewis Nebel\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = Grimes Hill, Eric Lewis, Lewis Nebel\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1903|11|03|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Staten Island]], [[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1967|05|03|1903|11|03}}\n| death_place = [[Laguna Beach, California|Laguna Beach]], [[California]]\n| occupation  = Novelist, short story writer\n| nationality = American\n| period      = \n| genre       = [[Crime fiction]], [[Mystery fiction]], [[Romance fiction]]\n| spouse      = \n| notableworks  = ''Sleepers East'' (1933), ''But Not the End'' (1934), ''Fifty Roads to Town'' (1936)\nSerialized Characters: Jack Cardigan, Donny Donahue, MacBride and Kennedy\n| children    = \n}}\n\n'''Frederick Lewis Nebel''' (November 3, 1903 - May 3, 1967), was an [[United States|American]] author with over 300 works to his credit, best known for his [[hardboiled]] [[detective fiction]].<ref name=\"nolan\">{{cite book | author = Nolan, William F. | title = The Black Mask Boys:Masters in the Hard-Boiled School of Detective Fiction | publisher = Mystery Press | location = New York | year = 1985 | isbn = 978-0-892-96931-9 }}</ref> Nebel was a prolific writer, penning up to five thousand words a day, often keeping five to six serial heroes in action from week to week for [[Pulp magazine|the pulps]]. Nebel also wrote three novels and many of his works were adapted for the screen.<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"imdb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0623862/ \"Frederick Nebel (1903 - 1967),\"] [[IMDb]], retrieved May 23, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in Staten Island, New York, Nebel dropped out of school at 15 after only one day in high school.<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"penzler1\">{{cite book | editor = Penzler, Otto | title = The Black Lizard Big Book of Black Mask Stories | publisher = Vintage Crime / Black Lizard | location = New York | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-0-307-45543-7 }}</ref> He worked as a dockhand and a valet before moving to Canada where he worked as a farmhand on his great-uncle\u2019s homestead. He enjoyed the wilderness and became a self-taught expert in Canadian history. This expertise helped launch his career writing adventure stories for ''Northwest Stories'', beginning in 1925.<ref name=\"detnovel\">[http://www.detnovel.com/Nebel.html \"Frederick Lewis Nebel (1903-1966),\"] [http://www.detnovel.com/ Detnovel.com], retrieved May 12, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"thrilling\">[http://www.thrillingdetective.com/trivia/nebel \"Frederick Nebel,\"] [http://www.thrillingdetective.com/ The Thrilling Detective Website], retrieved May 12, 2018.</ref> He returned to New York and got a job working as a brakeman on passenger trains and writing in his spare time.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Pulp magazines===\nIn 1926, Nebel sold his first ''[[Black Mask (magazine)|Black Mask]]'' story, \u201cThe Breaks of the Game,\u201d to editor Phil Cody. That same year [[Joseph Shaw (editor)|Joseph Shaw]] took over as editor, and throughout his tenure with the magazine, he mentored Nebel as he published his work.<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"detnovel\"/> Over the next 12 years, Nebel published at a fast pace, writing up to 5000 words a day, while publishing in ''Black Mask'' and numerous other pulp magazines, including ''[[Action Stories]]'', ''Danger Trail'', ''Dime Detective'' and ''Sea Stories''.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\nShaw encouraged his authors to develop series characters, and Nebel created the detective duo of Captain Steve MacBride and newspaper reporter Kennedy of fictional \u201cRichmond City\u201d.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> MacBride was a hardboiled homicide detective while drunken, wisecracking Kennedy provided comic relief.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/><ref>{{cite book | editor = Penzler, Otto | title = The Black Lizard Big Book of Pulps | publisher = Vintage Crime / Black Lizard | location = New York | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-307-28048-0}}</ref> The pair was featured in 36 of Nebel\u2019s stories spanning 8 years.[6] In the 1930s, Nebel sold the rights to MacBride and Kennedy to [[Warner Bros.]], who made nine film adaptations.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/><ref name=\"powell\">{{cite book | editor = Powell, Steven | title = 100 American Crime Writers | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = New York | year = 2012 | isbn = 978-0-230-52537-5 }}</ref> The [[CBS Radio]] series ''Meet MacBride'', beginning in 1936, was also adapted from the series.<ref name=\"penzler1\"/> \n\nNebel created Donny \u201cTough Dick\u201d Donahue at the request of Shaw for a character similar to [[Dashiel Hammett|Dashiel Hammett\u2019s]] [[Sam Spade]].<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"powell\"/> Following the huge success of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (novel)|The Maltese Falcon]]'', Shaw wanted more Spade stories but Hammett, a personal friend of Nebel\u2019s, had quit the pulps for Hollywood.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> Donahue was an ex-cop discharged for not giving into corruption, now working for the Inter-State Detective Agency.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/> From 1930 to 1935, Nebel wrote 15 Donahue stories for ''Black Mask''.<ref name=\"detnovel\"/>    \n\nFrom 1931-1937, Nebel wrote nearly 50 stories for ''Dime Detective'' featuring the character Jack Cardigan, a tough, Irish detective working for the Cosmos Detective Agency in [[St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite book | editor = Penzler, Otto | title = The Black Lizard Big Book of Pulps | publisher = Vintage Crime / Black Lizard | location = New York | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-307-28048-0}}</ref>\n\nOther series characters created by Nebel include: Bill Gales and Mike McGill for ''Air Stories'', Brinkhaus for ''Detective Fiction Weekly'', Corporate Chet Tyson for ''Northwest Stories'', and The Driftin\u2019 Kid for Lariat.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\nNebel sometimes wrote under the [[pen name|pen names]] Lewis Nebel, Eric Lewis and Grimes Hill,<ref name=\"nolan\"/><ref name=\"powell\"/> a name derived from Grymes Hill, near where he was born on Staten Island.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n===Novels and screen adaptations===\nIn 1933, [[Little, Brown and Company|Little, Brown]] published Nebel\u2019s first novel, ''Sleepers East'', based on his early experience as a brakeman on passenger trains.<ref name=\"detnovel\"/> The thriller is set entirely on a ten-hour train ride from the Midwest to New York.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]'', while critical of the genre conventions of a story set on a train, praised Nebel for providing \"thrills a-plenty.\" \"Though lacking credibility as to plot, the story has full measure of action, suspense and emotional conflict.\"<ref name=\"nytimes1933\">[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/06/25/105396143.html?pageNumber=42 \"Drama on a Train; SLEEPERS EAST. By Frederick Nobel. 283 pp. Boston: Little, Brown & Co. $2. Latest Works of Fiction,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/06/25/105396143.pdf | Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', June 25, 1933.</ref> The novel was later adapted to the screen as ''[[Sleepers West]]'' (1941).<ref name=\"penzler1\"/> In 1934, he wrote ''But Not the End'', a novel set in Depression-era New York City. The book was praised for its \"brilliant divergences from the standardized patterns of depression era fiction.<ref name=\"nytimes1934\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1934/03/18/archives/the-new-poor-but-not-the-end-by-frederick-nebel-304-pp-boston.html \"The New Poor; BUT NOT THE END. By Frederick Nebel. 304 pp. Boston: Little, Brown & Co. $2.,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1934/03/18/93755675.pdf | Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', March 18, 1934.</ref> In 1936, he wrote the novel ''Fifty Roads to Town''. ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote,\"This is a first rate, virile piece of story-telling. It moves dramatically but in a restrained and effective manner toward its ultimate goal.\"<ref name=\"rossbach\">Mabel L. Rossbach, [https://www.nytimes.com/1936/02/02/archives/in-a-maine-hotel-fifty-roads-to-town-by-frederick-nebel-299-pp.html In a Maine Hotel; FIFTY ROADS TO TOWN. By Frederick Nebel. 299 pp. Boston: Little Brown & Co. $2,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1936/02/02/85231602.pdf | Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', February 2, 1936.</ref> It was adapted into a comedy film of the [[Fifty Roads to Town|same name]] starring [[Don Ameche]] in 1937.<ref name=\"powell\"/> \n\nHis story \u201cThe Bribe\u201d was adapted into the 1949 movie by the [[The Bribe|same name]], starring [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]], [[Ava Gardner]], [[Charles Laughton]], and [[Vincent Price]].<ref name=\"penzler1\"/><ref name=\"brady\">Thomas F. Brady, [https://www.nytimes.com/1948/04/08/archives/taylor-gardner-in-metro-picture-get-leads-in-the-bribe-fbi-story-of.html \"TAYLOR, GARDNER IN METRO PICTURE; Get Leads in 'The Bribe,' FBI Story of War Surplus Sales in Cuba -- Berman Producer,\"] [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1948/04/08/96421792.pdf | Archived] via the [[The New York Times#TimesMachine|TimesMachine]],''[[The New York Times]]'', April 8, 1948.</ref> On Television, his work was adapted for such shows as General Electric Theater and Studio One.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n===Slick magazines===\nAfter selling the film rights to ''Sleepers East'', Nebel hired agent Carl Brandt.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> After 12 years and more than 230 stories, Nebel stopped writing for the detective pulps in 1937 to focus on romance.<ref name=\"detnovel\"/> Under Brandt\u2019s guidance, Nebel began selling to higher-paying slick magazines such as ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[McCall\u2019s]]'', ''[[Redbook]]'', ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'' and ''[[Woman\u2019s Home Companion]]''.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> \n\nIn 1956 he returned to mystery writing biefly, publishing 6 more short stories for ''[[Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"powell\"/> His last story was published in 1962.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> \n\n==Personal life==\nNebel met his wife, Dorothy Blank, in Paris in 1928.<ref name=\"nolan\"/> They married in 1930 and moved to [[St. Louis]], where much of his fiction is set. In 1934, they moved to Connecticut and in 1937 they had a son, Christopher Nebel. Suffering from high blood pressure, Nebel moved to Laguna Beach, California in the late 1950s.<ref name=\"thrilling\"/><ref name=\"powell\"/>  In 1967 Nebel suffered a cerebral hemorrhage and died three days later at age sixty-three.<ref name=\"nolan\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nebel, Frederick Lewis}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Pulp fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederick_Nebel"}
{"title_page": "Liam O'Flaherty", "text_new": "{{for|the Irish footballer|Liam O'Flaherty (footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Liam O'Flaherty\n| image       = Liam O'Flaherty.jpeg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1896|8|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Inishmore]], Ireland\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1984|9|7|1896|8|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| occupation  = Author\n| nationality = Irish\n| period      = \n| movement    = Irish Renaissance\n| spouse      = [[Margaret Barrington]]\n| partner     =\n| children    = Pegeen, Joyce\n| relatives   = [[Tom Maidhc O'Flaherty|Tom O'Flaherty]], his brother<br />[[Breand\u00e1n \u00d3 hEithir]], his nephew<br />[[John Ford]], his cousin\n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n}}\n'''Liam O'Flaherty''' ({{lang-ga|Liam \u00d3 Flaithearta}}; 28 August 1896 \u2013 7 September 1984) was an Irish novelist, short-story writer and major figure in the [[Celtic Revival|Irish literary renaissance]]. He served on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] as a soldier in the [[Irish Guards]] and was badly injured. After the war, he was a founding member of the [[Communist Party of Ireland (1920)|Communist Party of Ireland]]. His brother [[Tom Maidhc O'Flaherty]] (also a writer) was also involved in radical politics and their father, [[Maidhc \u00d3 Flaithearta]], before them.  A native Irish-speaker from the [[Gaeltacht]], O'Flaherty wrote almost exclusively in English, except for a small number of short stories in the [[Irish language]].\n\n== Early years ==\n[[File:Inishmore1.jpg|thumb|East beach of [[Inishmore]], O'Flaherty's birthplace]]\n\nO'Flaherty was born, a son of [[Maidhc \u00d3 Flaithearta]] and Maggie Ganley, at Gort na gCapall, [[Inishmore]].  His family, descendants of the [[\u00d3 Flaithbertaigh]] family of [[Connemara]], were not well off. The [[Irish language]] was widely spoken in the area, and in the O'Flaherty household both English and Irish were used.<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, Breand\u00e1n, ''An Chaint sa tSr\u00e1idbhaile''. Comhar Teoranta, 1991, p. 166. {{ISBN|978-0-631-23580-4}}</ref>  O'Flaherty was an uncle of [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] commentator and writer, [[Breand\u00e1n \u00d3 hEithir]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/28/obituaries/breandan-o-heithir-irish-writer-dies-at-60.html \"Breandan O hEithir, Irish Writer, Dies at 60\"], ''The New York Times'', 1990-10-25.</ref>\n\nAt the age of twelve, he moved to [[County Tipperary]] to attend [[Rockwell College]].  Six years later, in 1914, he moved to [[Dublin]] to attend [[University College Dublin]] and the Dublin Diocesan<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dublindiocese.ie/archdiocese-overview/diocesan-curia/diocesan-offices/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430120158/http://www.dublindiocese.ie/archdiocese-overview/diocesan-curia/diocesan-offices/ |archive-date=30 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> teacher training college Holy Cross College ([[Clonliffe College]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenpages.ie/holycross-college-dublin-D3/|title=Holycross College|website=goldenpages.ie}}</ref> According to ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'', he also attended [[Belvedere College]] and [[Blackrock College]].\n\nHe intended to enter the priesthood and enrolled in the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]],<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/an-irishman-s-diary-1.577013?mode=amp|title=An Irishman's Diary|website=www.irishtimes.com}}</ref> but in 1917 he joined the [[British Army]] as a member of the [[Irish Guards]] in 1917 under the name 'Bill Ganly'.<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, p. 164</ref> serving on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. He found trench life devastatingly monotonous <ref>[http://www.turtlebunbury.com Turtle Bunbury], ''The Glorious Madness, Tales of The Irish and The Great War'', <br> Liam O'Flaherty - An Aran Islander at War, pp.122-24, Gill & Macmillan, Dublin 12 (2014) {{ISBN|978 0717 16234 5}}</ref> but was badly injured in September 1917 during the [[Battle of Langemarck (1917)|Battle of Langemarck]], near [[Ypres]] in [[West Flanders]]. It is speculated that the [[shell shock]] suffered was responsible for the mental illness which became apparent in 1933.\n\nAfter being discharged he went travelling. He joined the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] in [[Canada]] and while in New York joined the [[Communist Party USA]].<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\"/>\n\nHe returned from the front a [[Socialism|socialist]]. Having become interested in [[Marxism]] as a schoolboy,<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, p. 163</ref> atheistic and communistic beliefs evolved in his 20s and he was a founder member of the Communist Party of Ireland.<ref>Turtle Bunbury: p. 123</ref>  In 1922, two days after the establishment of the [[Irish Free State]], O'Flaherty, who declared himself as Chairman of the Council of the Unemployed and other unemployed Dublin workers seized the Rotunda Concert Hall (the building was later separated from the [[Rotunda Hospital]] and is now divided between the [[Ambassador Cinema]] and the [[Gate Theatre]]) in Dublin and held it for four days flying a [[red flag (politics)|red flag]], in protest at \"the apathy of the authorities\". Free State troops forced their surrender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comeheretome.com/2010/08/27/raising-the-red-flag-at-the-rotunda-the-workers-occupation-of-january-1922/|title=Raising the Red Flag at the Rotunda. The workers occupation of January 1922.|date=27 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Turtle Bunbury: p.124\">Turtle Bunbury: p.124</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nAfter these events, O'Flaherty left Ireland and moved first to England where, destitute and jobless, he took to writing.  In 1923, at the age of 27, O'Flaherty published his first novel, ''[[Thy Neighbour's Wife]]''.  In 1925 he scored immediate success with his best-selling novel ''[[The Informer (novel)|The Informer]]'' about a rebel with confused ideals in the [[Irish War of Independence]], which won him the 1925 [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] for fiction.<ref name=\"Turtle Bunbury: p.124\"/> Four years later his next short novel ''[[Return of the Brute]]'', set in the World War I trenches, proved another success.<ref name=\"Turtle Bunbury: p.124\"/>  He then travelled to the United States, where he lived in Hollywood for a short time.  The film director [[John Ford]], a cousin, later [[The Informer (1935 film)|made a film of The Informer]], in 1935. The novel had also previously been made into a film in 1929, [[The Informer (1929 film)|also called The Informer]], directed by Arthur Robison.  Many of O'Flaherty's works have the common theme of nature and Ireland. He was a distinguished [[short story]] writer.  He travelled in the United States and Europe, and the letters he wrote while travelling have now been published. He had a love of French and [[Russia|Russian culture]].\n\nMost of O'Flaherty's writing took place in the fourteen years starting with the publication of his first novel, 1923-1937 (between the ages of 27 and 41), when he wrote 14 of his 16 novels as well as many of his short stories, a play, and at least five non-fiction books.  {{citation needed span|text=In 1933 he suffered from the first of two mental breakdowns.|date=August 2017}}\n\nThe collection ''D\u00fail'', published in 1953 when his writing activity was coming to an end, contained 18 short stories in Irish.  Some of the stories in D\u00fail are similar to short stories O'Flaherty previously published in English.  According to Angeline A. Kelly, at least two of the 18, ''Daoine Bochta'' and ''An Fiach'', both written in 1925, were originally written in Irish.<ref name=\"kelly-intro\">{{cite book|last= Kelly|first= Angeline A.|date= 2000|title= Liam O'Flaherty: the Collected Stories, volume 1 (Introduction by A. A. Kelly)|isbn= 0-312-22903-8|quote= Introduction ... the whole body of Liam O'Flaherty's short story writing, composed 1922-1958 ... Most of these stories have been previously published in seven different collections (1922-1976), plus one Irish language collection of eighteen stories, ''D\u00fail'' ... At least two of the Irish stories <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Daoine Bochta''<nowiki>'</nowiki> and <nowiki>'</nowiki>''An Fiach''<nowiki>'</nowiki> (both written in 1925) were originally composed in Irish.  The other stories in Irish were translated or recomposed into their English language version.  Until the 1950s it was difficult to get Irish language work published.|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/collectedstories00ofla}}</ref>  The other stories may have begun as unpublished stories written in Irish, but which got their first publication by being reformulated into English, before finally being published in their original Irish version in D\u00fail.  This was probably the case for ''D\u00edoltas'', for example, which became ''The Pedlar's Revenge''.<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, p. 166</ref><ref>\u00d3 Flaithearta, Liam. ''D\u00fail'', S\u00e1irs\u00e9al agus Dill, 1953/1979. {{ISBN|0-901374-07-5}}</ref>  This collection, now widely admired, had a poor reception at the time and this seems to have discouraged him from proceeding with an Irish language novel he had in hand.  In a letter written to ''The Sunday Times'' years later, he confessed to a certain ambivalence regarding his work in Irish, and spoke of other Irish writers who received little praise for their work in the language. This gave rise to some controversy.\n\n== Later years ==\n\nHis last novel was published in 1950, and his last published short story was 1958.<ref name=\"kelly-intro\" />  One biography comments of his later years that he \"spent much time travelling and lived comfortably and quietly outside the spotlight\".<ref name=\"ohare\">''A Companion to the British and Irish Short Story'', Chapter 19, \"The Short Stories of Liam O'Flaherty\", pages 221-226.</ref>  Before his death he left the Communist Party and returned to the Roman Catholic faith.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nO'Flaherty died on 7 September 1984, aged 88 in Dublin, and many of his works were subsequently republished. He is remembered today as a powerful writer and a strong voice in Irish culture.\n\n==Works==\n===Novels===\n* ''[[Thy Neighbour's Wife]]'' (1923)\n* ''The Black Soul'' (1924)\n* ''[[The Informer (novel)|The Informer]]'' (1925)\n** adapted to film twice: [[The Informer (1929 film)]], and [[The Informer (1935 film)]] \n* ''Mr. Gilhooley'' (1926)\n* ''The Wilderness'' (serialised 1927, gathered in book form and republished 1986)\n* ''The Assassin'' (1928)\n* ''[[Return of the Brute]]'' (1929)\n* ''The House of Gold'' (1929), the first novel banned by the [[Irish Free State]], for alleged indecency. Republished in 2013.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/state-s-first-banned-book-to-be-published-for-first-time-in-80-years-1.1425131 State's first banned book to be published for first time in 80 years] Irish Times, 2013-06-12.</ref>\n* ''The Ecstasy Of Angus'' (1931)\n** O'Flaherty recorded a spoken word version, released as a double-album record in 1978 by [[Claddagh Records]], Dublin, catalogue no. CCT 15 & 16.\n* ''The Puritan'' (1932)\n* ''Skerrett'' (1932)\n* ''The Martyr'' (1933)\nHarry Potter and the wizards bum\n* ''Hollywood Cemetery'' (1935)\n* ''[[Famine (O'Flaherty novel)|Famine]]'' (1937)\n* ''Land'' (1946)\n* ''[[Insurrection (1950 novel)|Insurrection]]'' (1950)\n\n===Short stories and collections===\n\nIn 1999, when compiling all of O'Flaherty's short stories A. A. Kelly found a total of 183.<ref name=\"kelly-intro\" />  These were published in a 3 volume set, ''Liam O'Flaherty: The Collected Stories''.  The original publication of these stories was spread between over a dozen journals and magazines.  Many collections have also been published, including collections containing selections of stories from previous collections.  Kelly's introduction to her collection mentions that most of O'Flaherty's stories can be found in eight original collections.  The front flap of the hardback book's cover gives the names of six of these:\n\n* Spring Sowing\n* The Tent\n* The Mountain Tavern\n* Two Lovely Beasts and Other Stories (1950)\n* D\u00fail (1953)\n* The Pedlar's Revenge and Other Short Stories (1976, but written much earlier)\n\nHis best known short story is ''[[The Sniper (story)|The Sniper]]''.  Others include ''Civil War'', ''The Shilling'', ''Going into Exile'', ''Night Porter'',<ref>1947 January\u2013February Story Magazine pages 23 to 32</ref> ''A Red Petticoat'', and ''His First Flight'' \u2013 about the nervousness before doing something new.\n\n===Theatre===\n\n* Darkness\n** The play was performed in Irish, as ''Dorchadas'', in 1926\n\n===For children===\n\n* ''The Fairy Goose and Two Other Stories'' (1927) London: Crosby Gaige [https://books.google.com/books/about/The_fairy_goose.html?id=EM4_AQAAIAAJ  .]\n* ''The Wild Swan and Other Stories'' (1932) London Joiner & Steele\n* ''All Things Come of Age: A Rabbit Story'', short story, included in ''The Pedlar's Revenge and Other Stories''\n* ''The Test of Courage'', short story, included in ''The Pedlar's Revenge and Other Stories''\n\n===Non-fiction===\n\n* ''Life of Tim Healy'' (1927), a biography\n* ''A Tourist's Guide To Ireland'' (1929), satirical\n* ''Two Years'', or ''Two Years of My Life'' (1930), memoirs\n* ''I went to Russia'' (1931), memoirs\n* ''Shame The Devil'' (1934), memoirs\n* ''The Letters Of Liam O'Flaherty'' (1996), published posthumously, edited by Angeline A. Kelly, {{ISBN|0-86327-380-7}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Peadar O'Donnell]] \u2014 revolutionary socialist from the Donegal Gaeltacht\n\n==Biographies and studies of his work==\n\nBooks about O'Flaherty and his works:\n\n* Angeline A. Kelly, ''Liam O'Flaherty, the Storyteller'', The Macmillan Press, London 1976, {{ISBN|0-333-19768-2}}\n* George Jefferson, ''Liam O'Flaherty: A Descriptive Bibliography of his Works'', Wolfhound Press, Dublin 1993, {{ISBN|0-86327-188-X}}\n\nChapters or papers:<!-- PLEASE let's not start listing short articles of 5 pages or less from newspapers and magazines -->\n\n* Elisabeth Schnack, in German, chapter \"Liam O'Flaherty\" of ''M\u00fcssen K\u00fcnstler einsam sein?'' (''Must Artists be Lonely?''), pp.&nbsp;47\u201360, Pendo Verlag, Zurich 1991, {{ISBN|3-85842-191-X}}\n\nFilm documentaries:\n\n* ''Idir Dh\u00e1 Theanga'' (Between Two Languages) is a 2002 documentary film about Liam \u00d3 Flatharta by [[Alan Titley]] and Mac Dara \u00d3 Curraidh\u00edn.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Liam O'Flaherty}}\n* [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/new_hibernia_review/v007/7.1cronin.html Liam O'Flaherty and Duil] - about O'Flaherty's example in not writing in Irish\n* [http://comeheretome.wordpress.com/2010/08/27/raising-the-red-flag-at-the-rotunda-the-workers-occupation-of-january-1922/ Liam O'Flaherty and the raising the Red Flag at the Rotunda. The workers' occupation of the Rotunda of January 1922.]\n* {{LCAuth|n79135499|Liam O'Flaherty|94|ue}}\n\nSelected short stories accessible online:\n* [http://www.classicshorts.com/stories/sniper.html The Sniper]\n* [http://www.ireland-information.com/thereapingrace.htm The Reaping Race]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120218184422/http://www.bookconsult.com/LiamOFlaherty/brute.htm An extract from Return of the Brute]\n\n{{Liam O'Flaherty}}\n{{Gaelic literature}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oflaherty, Liam}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Industrial Workers of the World members]]\n[[Category:Irish Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Irish communists]]\n[[Category:Irish male novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Irish short story writers]]\n[[Category:Irish people of World War I]]\n[[Category:James Tait Black Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:People educated at Belvedere College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Blackrock College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rockwell College]]\n[[Category:People from County Galway]]\n[[Category:People of the Irish Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Irish footballer|Liam O'Flaherty (footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Liam O'Flaherty\n| image       = Liam O'Flaherty.jpeg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1896|8|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Inishmore]], Ireland\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1984|9|7|1896|8|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n| occupation  = Author\n| nationality = Irish\n| period      = \n| movement    = Irish Renaissance\n| spouse      = [[Margaret Barrington]]\n| partner     =\n| children    = Pegeen, Joyce\n| relatives   = [[Tom Maidhc O'Flaherty|Tom O'Flaherty]], his brother<br />[[Breand\u00e1n \u00d3 hEithir]], his nephew<br />[[John Ford]], his cousin\n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n}}\n'''Liam O'Flaherty''' ({{lang-ga|Liam \u00d3 Flaithearta}}; 28 August 1896 \u2013 7 September 1984) was an Irish novelist, short-story writer and major figure in the [[Celtic Revival|Irish literary renaissance]]. He served on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] as a soldier in the [[Irish Guards]] and was badly injured. After the war, he was a founding member of the [[Communist Party of Ireland (1920)|Communist Party of Ireland]]. His brother [[Tom Maidhc O'Flaherty]] (also a writer) was also involved in radical politics and their father, [[Maidhc \u00d3 Flaithearta]], before them.  A native Irish-speaker from the [[Gaeltacht]], O'Flaherty wrote almost exclusively in English, except for a small number of short stories in the [[Irish language]].\n\n== Early years ==\n[[File:Inishmore1.jpg|thumb|East beach of [[Inishmore]], O'Flaherty's birthplace]]\n\nO'Flaherty was born, a son of [[Maidhc \u00d3 Flaithearta]] and Maggie Ganley, at Gort na gCapall, [[Inishmore]].  His family, descendants of the [[\u00d3 Flaithbertaigh]] family of [[Connemara]], were not well off. The [[Irish language]] was widely spoken in the area, and in the O'Flaherty household both English and Irish were used.<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, Breand\u00e1n, ''An Chaint sa tSr\u00e1idbhaile''. Comhar Teoranta, 1991, p. 166. {{ISBN|978-0-631-23580-4}}</ref>  O'Flaherty was an uncle of [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] commentator and writer, [[Breand\u00e1n \u00d3 hEithir]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/28/obituaries/breandan-o-heithir-irish-writer-dies-at-60.html \"Breandan O hEithir, Irish Writer, Dies at 60\"], ''The New York Times'', 1990-10-25.</ref>\n\nAt the age of twelve, he moved to [[County Tipperary]] to attend [[Rockwell College]].  Six years later, in 1914, he moved to [[Dublin]] to attend [[University College Dublin]] and the Dublin Diocesan<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dublindiocese.ie/archdiocese-overview/diocesan-curia/diocesan-offices/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=12 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430120158/http://www.dublindiocese.ie/archdiocese-overview/diocesan-curia/diocesan-offices/ |archive-date=30 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> teacher training college Holy Cross College ([[Clonliffe College]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenpages.ie/holycross-college-dublin-D3/|title=Holycross College|website=goldenpages.ie}}</ref> According to ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'', he also attended [[Belvedere College]] and [[Blackrock College]].\n\nHe intended to enter the priesthood and enrolled in the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]],<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/an-irishman-s-diary-1.577013?mode=amp|title=An Irishman's Diary|website=www.irishtimes.com}}</ref> but in 1917 he joined the [[British Army]] as a member of the [[Irish Guards]] in 1917 under the name 'Bill Ganly'.<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, p. 164</ref> serving on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. He found trench life devastatingly monotonous <ref>[http://www.turtlebunbury.com Turtle Bunbury], ''The Glorious Madness, Tales of The Irish and The Great War'', <br> Liam O'Flaherty - An Aran Islander at War, pp.122-24, Gill & Macmillan, Dublin 12 (2014) {{ISBN|978 0717 16234 5}}</ref> but was badly injured in September 1917 during the [[Battle of Langemarck (1917)|Battle of Langemarck]], near [[Ypres]] in [[West Flanders]]. It is speculated that the [[shell shock]] suffered was responsible for the mental illness which became apparent in 1933.\n\nAfter being discharged he went travelling. He joined the [[Industrial Workers of the World]] in [[Canada]] and while in New York joined the [[Communist Party USA]].<ref name=\"irishtimes.com\"/>\n\nHe returned from the front a [[Socialism|socialist]]. Having become interested in [[Marxism]] as a schoolboy,<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, p. 163</ref> atheistic and communistic beliefs evolved in his 20s and he was a founder member of the Communist Party of Ireland.<ref>Turtle Bunbury: p. 123</ref>  In 1922, two days after the establishment of the [[Irish Free State]], O'Flaherty, who declared himself as Chairman of the Council of the Unemployed and other unemployed Dublin workers seized the Rotunda Concert Hall (the building was later separated from the [[Rotunda Hospital]] and is now divided between the [[Ambassador Cinema]] and the [[Gate Theatre]]) in Dublin and held it for four days flying a [[red flag (politics)|red flag]], in protest at \"the apathy of the authorities\". Free State troops forced their surrender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comeheretome.com/2010/08/27/raising-the-red-flag-at-the-rotunda-the-workers-occupation-of-january-1922/|title=Raising the Red Flag at the Rotunda. The workers occupation of January 1922.|date=27 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Turtle Bunbury: p.124\">Turtle Bunbury: p.124</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nAfter these events, O'Flaherty left Ireland and moved first to England where, destitute and jobless, he took to writing.  In 1923, at the age of 27, O'Flaherty published his first novel, ''[[Thy Neighbour's Wife]]''.  In 1925 he scored immediate success with his best-selling novel ''[[The Informer (novel)|The Informer]]'' about a rebel with confused ideals in the [[Irish War of Independence]], which won him the 1925 [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] for fiction.<ref name=\"Turtle Bunbury: p.124\"/> Four years later his next short novel ''[[Return of the Brute]]'', set in the World War I trenches, proved another success.<ref name=\"Turtle Bunbury: p.124\"/>  He then travelled to the United States, where he lived in Hollywood for a short time.  The film director [[John Ford]], a cousin, later [[The Informer (1935 film)|made a film of The Informer]], in 1935. The novel had also previously been made into a film in 1929, [[The Informer (1929 film)|also called The Informer]], directed by Arthur Robison.  Many of O'Flaherty's works have the common theme of nature and Ireland. He was a distinguished [[short story]] writer.  He travelled in the United States and Europe, and the letters he wrote while travelling have now been published. He had a love of French and [[Russia|Russian culture]].\n\nMost of O'Flaherty's writing took place in the fourteen years starting with the publication of his first novel, 1923-1937 (between the ages of 27 and 41), when he wrote 14 of his 16 novels as well as many of his short stories, a play, and at least five non-fiction books.  {{citation needed span|text=In 1933 he suffered from the first of two mental breakdowns.|date=August 2017}}\n\nThe collection ''D\u00fail'', published in 1953 when his writing activity was coming to an end, contained 18 short stories in Irish.  Some of the stories in D\u00fail are similar to short stories O'Flaherty previously published in English.  According to Angeline A. Kelly, at least two of the 18, ''Daoine Bochta'' and ''An Fiach'', both written in 1925, were originally written in Irish.<ref name=\"kelly-intro\">{{cite book|last= Kelly|first= Angeline A.|date= 2000|title= Liam O'Flaherty: the Collected Stories, volume 1 (Introduction by A. A. Kelly)|isbn= 0-312-22903-8|quote= Introduction ... the whole body of Liam O'Flaherty's short story writing, composed 1922-1958 ... Most of these stories have been previously published in seven different collections (1922-1976), plus one Irish language collection of eighteen stories, ''D\u00fail'' ... At least two of the Irish stories <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Daoine Bochta''<nowiki>'</nowiki> and <nowiki>'</nowiki>''An Fiach''<nowiki>'</nowiki> (both written in 1925) were originally composed in Irish.  The other stories in Irish were translated or recomposed into their English language version.  Until the 1950s it was difficult to get Irish language work published.|url-access= registration|url= https://archive.org/details/collectedstories00ofla}}</ref>  The other stories may have begun as unpublished stories written in Irish, but which got their first publication by being reformulated into English, before finally being published in their original Irish version in D\u00fail.  This was probably the case for ''D\u00edoltas'', for example, which became ''The Pedlar's Revenge''.<ref>\u00d3 hEithir, p. 166</ref><ref>\u00d3 Flaithearta, Liam. ''D\u00fail'', S\u00e1irs\u00e9al agus Dill, 1953/1979. {{ISBN|0-901374-07-5}}</ref>  This collection, now widely admired, had a poor reception at the time and this seems to have discouraged him from proceeding with an Irish language novel he had in hand.  In a letter written to ''The Sunday Times'' years later, he confessed to a certain ambivalence regarding his work in Irish, and spoke of other Irish writers who received little praise for their work in the language. This gave rise to some controversy.\n\n== Later years ==\n\nHis last novel was published in 1950, and his last published short story was 1958.<ref name=\"kelly-intro\" />  One biography comments of his later years that he \"spent much time travelling and lived comfortably and quietly outside the spotlight\".<ref name=\"ohare\">''A Companion to the British and Irish Short Story'', Chapter 19, \"The Short Stories of Liam O'Flaherty\", pages 221-226.</ref>  Before his death he left the Communist Party and returned to the Roman Catholic faith.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nO'Flaherty died on 7 September 1984, aged 88 in Dublin, and many of his works were subsequently republished. He is remembered today as a powerful writer and a strong voice in Irish culture.\n\n==Works==\n===Novels===\n* ''[[Thy Neighbour's Wife]]'' (1923)\n* ''The Black Soul'' (1924)\n* ''[[The Informer (novel)|The Informer]]'' (1925)\n** adapted to film twice: [[The Informer (1929 film)]], and [[The Informer (1935 film)]] \n* ''Mr. Gilhooley'' (1926)\n* ''The Wilderness'' (serialised 1927, gathered in book form and republished 1986)\n* ''The Assassin'' (1928)\n* ''[[Return of the Brute]]'' (1929)\n* ''The House of Gold'' (1929), the first novel banned by the [[Irish Free State]], for alleged indecency. Republished in 2013.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/state-s-first-banned-book-to-be-published-for-first-time-in-80-years-1.1425131 State's first banned book to be published for first time in 80 years] Irish Times, 2013-06-12.</ref>\n* ''The Ecstasy Of Angus'' (1931)\n** O'Flaherty recorded a spoken word version, released as a double-album record in 1978 by [[Claddagh Records]], Dublin, catalogue no. CCT 15 & 16.\n* ''The Puritan'' (1932)\n* ''Skerrett'' (1932)\n* ''The Martyr'' (1933)\n* ''Hollywood Cemetery'' (1935)\n* ''[[Famine (O'Flaherty novel)|Famine]]'' (1937)\n* ''Land'' (1946)\n* ''[[Insurrection (1950 novel)|Insurrection]]'' (1950)\n\n===Short stories and collections===\n\nIn 1999, when compiling all of O'Flaherty's short stories A. A. Kelly found a total of 183.<ref name=\"kelly-intro\" />  These were published in a 3 volume set, ''Liam O'Flaherty: The Collected Stories''.  The original publication of these stories was spread between over a dozen journals and magazines.  Many collections have also been published, including collections containing selections of stories from previous collections.  Kelly's introduction to her collection mentions that most of O'Flaherty's stories can be found in eight original collections.  The front flap of the hardback book's cover gives the names of six of these:\n\n* Spring Sowing\n* The Tent\n* The Mountain Tavern\n* Two Lovely Beasts and Other Stories (1950)\n* D\u00fail (1953)\n* The Pedlar's Revenge and Other Short Stories (1976, but written much earlier)\n\nHis best known short story is ''[[The Sniper (story)|The Sniper]]''.  Others include ''Civil War'', ''The Shilling'', ''Going into Exile'', ''Night Porter'',<ref>1947 January\u2013February Story Magazine pages 23 to 32</ref> ''A Red Petticoat'', and ''His First Flight'' \u2013 about the nervousness before doing something new.\n\n===Theatre===\n\n* Darkness\n** The play was performed in Irish, as ''Dorchadas'', in 1926\n\n===For children===\n\n* ''The Fairy Goose and Two Other Stories'' (1927) London: Crosby Gaige [https://books.google.com/books/about/The_fairy_goose.html?id=EM4_AQAAIAAJ  .]\n* ''The Wild Swan and Other Stories'' (1932) London Joiner & Steele\n* ''All Things Come of Age: A Rabbit Story'', short story, included in ''The Pedlar's Revenge and Other Stories''\n* ''The Test of Courage'', short story, included in ''The Pedlar's Revenge and Other Stories''\n\n===Non-fiction===\n\n* ''Life of Tim Healy'' (1927), a biography\n* ''A Tourist's Guide To Ireland'' (1929), satirical\n* ''Two Years'', or ''Two Years of My Life'' (1930), memoirs\n* ''I went to Russia'' (1931), memoirs\n* ''Shame The Devil'' (1934), memoirs\n* ''The Letters Of Liam O'Flaherty'' (1996), published posthumously, edited by Angeline A. Kelly, {{ISBN|0-86327-380-7}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Peadar O'Donnell]] \u2014 revolutionary socialist from the Donegal Gaeltacht\n\n==Biographies and studies of his work==\n\nBooks about O'Flaherty and his works:\n\n* Angeline A. Kelly, ''Liam O'Flaherty, the Storyteller'', The Macmillan Press, London 1976, {{ISBN|0-333-19768-2}}\n* George Jefferson, ''Liam O'Flaherty: A Descriptive Bibliography of his Works'', Wolfhound Press, Dublin 1993, {{ISBN|0-86327-188-X}}\n\nChapters or papers:<!-- PLEASE let's not start listing short articles of 5 pages or less from newspapers and magazines -->\n\n* Elisabeth Schnack, in German, chapter \"Liam O'Flaherty\" of ''M\u00fcssen K\u00fcnstler einsam sein?'' (''Must Artists be Lonely?''), pp.&nbsp;47\u201360, Pendo Verlag, Zurich 1991, {{ISBN|3-85842-191-X}}\n\nFilm documentaries:\n\n* ''Idir Dh\u00e1 Theanga'' (Between Two Languages) is a 2002 documentary film about Liam \u00d3 Flatharta by [[Alan Titley]] and Mac Dara \u00d3 Curraidh\u00edn.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Liam O'Flaherty}}\n* [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/new_hibernia_review/v007/7.1cronin.html Liam O'Flaherty and Duil] - about O'Flaherty's example in not writing in Irish\n* [http://comeheretome.wordpress.com/2010/08/27/raising-the-red-flag-at-the-rotunda-the-workers-occupation-of-january-1922/ Liam O'Flaherty and the raising the Red Flag at the Rotunda. The workers' occupation of the Rotunda of January 1922.]\n* {{LCAuth|n79135499|Liam O'Flaherty|94|ue}}\n\nSelected short stories accessible online:\n* [http://www.classicshorts.com/stories/sniper.html The Sniper]\n* [http://www.ireland-information.com/thereapingrace.htm The Reaping Race]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120218184422/http://www.bookconsult.com/LiamOFlaherty/brute.htm An extract from Return of the Brute]\n\n{{Liam O'Flaherty}}\n{{Gaelic literature}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oflaherty, Liam}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Industrial Workers of the World members]]\n[[Category:Irish Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Irish communists]]\n[[Category:Irish male novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Irish short story writers]]\n[[Category:Irish people of World War I]]\n[[Category:James Tait Black Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:People educated at Belvedere College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Blackrock College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rockwell College]]\n[[Category:People from County Galway]]\n[[Category:People of the Irish Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "208.118.156.211", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liam_O%27Flaherty"}
{"title_page": "Slipper", "text_new": "{{Other uses}} \n\n[[File:Boy's Slippers Berlin Wool Work.jpg|thumb|right|Slippers]]\n[[File:Slippers on a shelf.jpg|thumb|Slippers on a shelf]]\n'''Slippers''' are light [were foot] that are easy to put on and off and are intended to be worn indoors, particularly at home.<ref>[https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/slipper Definition of ''slipper''] Retrieved 2017-09-12</ref>\n== History ==\n\nThe recorded history of slippers can be traced back to the 12th century when the Vietnamese had been wearing slippers. But in the West, the record can only be traced to 1478.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://betsyblue.co.uk/blogs/news/9037635-history-of-the-slipper|title=History of the Slipper|last=|first=|date=September 10, 2013|website=betsyblue.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iinuu.eu/en/wisdom/good-to-know/slipper-history|title=Slipper History|last=|first=|date=September 9, 2010|website=iinuu.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n{{refimprove section|date=June 2016}}\nThe following is a partial list of types of slippers:\n*Open-heel slippers \u2013 usually made with a fabric upper layer that encloses the top of the foot and the toes, but leaves the heel open. These are often distributed in expensive hotels, included with the cost of the room.\n*Closed slippers \u2013 slippers with a heel guard that prevents the foot from sliding out.\n*Slipper boots \u2013 slippers meant to look like boots. Often favored by women, they are typically furry boots with a fleece or soft lining, and a soft rubber sole. Modeled after [[sheepskin boots]], they may be worn outside.\n*Sandal slippers \u2013 cushioned [[sandal]]s with soft rubber or fabric soles, similar to [[Birkenstock]]'s cushioned sandals.\n* Evening slipper, also known as the \"Prince Albert\" slipper in reference to [[Albert, Prince Consort]]. It is made of velvet with leather soles and features a [[grosgrain]] bow or the wearer\u2019s initials embroidered in gold. \n\nSome slippers are made to resemble something other than a slipper and are sold as a [[novelty item]]. The slippers are usually made from soft and colorful materials and may come in the shapes of animals, animal paws, vehicles, cartoon characters, etc.\n\nNot all shoes with a soft fluffy interior are slippers. Any shoe with a rubber sole and laces is a normal outdoor shoe. In India, rubber [[chappal]]s (flip-flops) are worn as indoor shoes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Khanna |first=Parul |title=Hawai chappal the new fashion accessory! |url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/fashion-and-trends/hawai-chappal-the-new-fashion-accessory/story-ApEvMe8tiIjRDhcsizQaWI.html |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=3 October 2009 |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe fictional character [[Cinderella]] is said to have worn glass slippers; in modern parlance, they would probably be called glass [[high heels]]. This motif was introduced in Charles Perrault's 1697 version of the tale, \"Cendrillon ou la petite pantoufle de verre\" (\"Cinderella, or The Little Glass Slipper\"). For some years it was debated that this detail was a mistranslation and the slippers in the story were instead made of fur (French: ''vair''), but this interpretation has since been discredited by folklorists.<ref>Tatar, Maria. ''The Annotated Classic Fairy Tales.'' New York: W. W. Norton & Company, 2002.</ref>\n\nDerek \"The Slipper Man\" Fan holds the [[Guinness World Records]] record for wearing a pair of dress slippers for 23 years straight as of June 30, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/4861734.Free_slippers_for_elderly_city_residents/ |title=Free slippers for elderly city residents |work=[[Southern Daily Echo|Daily Echo]]|date=2010-01-20 |accessdate=2014-01-31}}</ref>{{dubious|reason=Can't find this on Guinness World Records website|date=December 2018}}\n\nA pair of [[ruby shoes\u00e0]] worn by [[Judy Garland]] in ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' sold at Christie's in June 1988 for $165,000. The same pair was resold in May 2000 for $666,000. On both occasions they were the most expensive shoes from a film to be sold at auction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-expensive-shoes-from-a-film-sold-at-auction|website=guinnessworldrecords.com|title=Most expensive shoes from a film sold at auction|date=|accessdate=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n''Grandpa's Slippers'' is an award-winning book by [[Joy Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/Writers/Profiles/Watson,%20Joy |title=Watson, Joy |publisher=bookcouncil.org.nz |date= |accessdate=2014-01-31}}</ref>\n\nIn Hawaii and many islands of The [[Caribbean]], slippers, or \"slippahs\" is used for describing [[flip-flops]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\nThe term 'house shoes' (elided into ''how-shuze'') is common in the [[American South]].<ref>Cassidy, Frederic Gomes, and Joan Houston Hall (eds). (2002) ''Dictionary of American Regional English''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bunny slippers]]\n* [[Moccasin]]s\n* [[Lady's slipper orchid]]s\n* [[Ruby slippers]]\n* [[Slippering]] (punishment)\n* [[Uwabaki]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Footwear}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Slippers}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline}}\n\n\n[[Category:Footwear]]\n[[Category:Shoes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}} \n\n[[File:Boy's Slippers Berlin Wool Work.jpg|thumb|right|Slippers]]\n[[File:Slippers on a shelf.jpg|thumb|Slippers on a shelf]]\n'''Slippers''' are light [[footwear]] that are easy to put on and off and are intended to be worn indoors, particularly at home.<ref>[https://www.collinsdictionary.com/us/dictionary/english/slipper Definition of ''slipper''] Retrieved 2017-09-12</ref>\n== History ==\n\nThe recorded history of slippers can be traced back to the 12th century when the Vietnamese had been wearing slippers. But in the West, the record can only be traced to 1478.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://betsyblue.co.uk/blogs/news/9037635-history-of-the-slipper|title=History of the Slipper|last=|first=|date=September 10, 2013|website=betsyblue.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iinuu.eu/en/wisdom/good-to-know/slipper-history|title=Slipper History|last=|first=|date=September 9, 2010|website=iinuu.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n{{refimprove section|date=June 2016}}\nThe following is a partial list of types of slippers:\n*Open-heel slippers \u2013 usually made with a fabric upper layer that encloses the top of the foot and the toes, but leaves the heel open. These are often distributed in expensive hotels, included with the cost of the room.\n*Closed slippers \u2013 slippers with a heel guard that prevents the foot from sliding out.\n*Slipper boots \u2013 slippers meant to look like boots. Often favored by women, they are typically furry boots with a fleece or soft lining, and a soft rubber sole. Modeled after [[sheepskin boots]], they may be worn outside.\n*Sandal slippers \u2013 cushioned [[sandal]]s with soft rubber or fabric soles, similar to [[Birkenstock]]'s cushioned sandals.\n* Evening slipper, also known as the \"Prince Albert\" slipper in reference to [[Albert, Prince Consort]]. It is made of velvet with leather soles and features a [[grosgrain]] bow or the wearer\u2019s initials embroidered in gold. \n\nSome slippers are made to resemble something other than a slipper and are sold as a [[novelty item]]. The slippers are usually made from soft and colorful materials and may come in the shapes of animals, animal paws, vehicles, cartoon characters, etc.\n\nNot all shoes with a soft fluffy interior are slippers. Any shoe with a rubber sole and laces is a normal outdoor shoe. In India, rubber [[chappal]]s (flip-flops) are worn as indoor shoes.<ref>{{cite news |last=Khanna |first=Parul |title=Hawai chappal the new fashion accessory! |url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/fashion-and-trends/hawai-chappal-the-new-fashion-accessory/story-ApEvMe8tiIjRDhcsizQaWI.html |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=3 October 2009 |accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe fictional character [[Cinderella]] is said to have worn glass slippers; in modern parlance, they would probably be called glass [[high heels]]. This motif was introduced in Charles Perrault's 1697 version of the tale, \"Cendrillon ou la petite pantoufle de verre\" (\"Cinderella, or The Little Glass Slipper\"). For some years it was debated that this detail was a mistranslation and the slippers in the story were instead made of fur (French: ''vair''), but this interpretation has since been discredited by folklorists.<ref>Tatar, Maria. ''The Annotated Classic Fairy Tales.'' New York: W. W. Norton & Company, 2002.</ref>\n\nDerek \"The Slipper Man\" Fan holds the [[Guinness World Records]] record for wearing a pair of dress slippers for 23 years straight as of June 30, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/4861734.Free_slippers_for_elderly_city_residents/ |title=Free slippers for elderly city residents |work=[[Southern Daily Echo|Daily Echo]]|date=2010-01-20 |accessdate=2014-01-31}}</ref>{{dubious|reason=Can't find this on Guinness World Records website|date=December 2018}}\n\nA pair of [[ruby slippers]] worn by [[Judy Garland]] in ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' sold at Christie's in June 1988 for $165,000. The same pair was resold in May 2000 for $666,000. On both occasions they were the most expensive shoes from a film to be sold at auction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-expensive-shoes-from-a-film-sold-at-auction|website=guinnessworldrecords.com|title=Most expensive shoes from a film sold at auction|date=|accessdate=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\n''Grandpa's Slippers'' is an award-winning book by [[Joy Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/Writers/Profiles/Watson,%20Joy |title=Watson, Joy |publisher=bookcouncil.org.nz |date= |accessdate=2014-01-31}}</ref>\n\nIn Hawaii and many islands of The [[Caribbean]], slippers, or \"slippahs\" is used for describing [[flip-flops]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\nThe term 'house shoes' (elided into ''how-shuze'') is common in the [[American South]].<ref>Cassidy, Frederic Gomes, and Joan Houston Hall (eds). (2002) ''Dictionary of American Regional English''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: Harvard University Press.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bunny slippers]]\n* [[Moccasin]]s\n* [[Lady's slipper orchid]]s\n* [[Ruby slippers]]\n* [[Slippering]] (punishment)\n* [[Uwabaki]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Footwear}}\n{{Clothing}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Slippers}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline}}\n\n\n[[Category:Footwear]]\n[[Category:Shoes]]\n", "name_user": "Whello", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slipper"}
{"title_page": "Rival Sons", "text_new": "{{excessive detail|date=October 2018}}\n{{Self-published|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Rival Sons\n| image           = Rival Sons Vienna.jpg\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Long Beach, California]], <br /> [[United States]]\n| genre           ={{flatlist|\n*[[Blues rock]]\n*[[hard rock]]\n*{{nowrap|[[rock and roll]]}}\n}}\n| years_active    = {{start date|2009}}\u2013present\n| label           = {{flatlist|\n*[[Earache Records|Earache]]\n*[[Warner Music Group]]\n*[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n*[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n*[[Low Country Sound]] \n}}\n| website         = {{URL|rivalsons.com}}\n| current_members = \n* [[Jay Buchanan]]\n* [[Scott Holiday]]\n* [[Michael Miley]]\n* [[Dave Beste]]\n| past_members    = Robin Everhart\n| associated_acts = [[Dave Cobb]] <br/> [[Vance Powell]] <br/> [[Veruca Salt]] <br/>  [[Bloody Beetroots]] }}\n\n'''Rival Sons''' are an American [[Rock music|rock]] band formed in [[Long Beach, California]] in 2009. The group consists of lead vocalist [[Jay Buchanan]], guitarist [[Scott Holiday]], bassist Dave Beste and drummer Michael Miley. The band is also joined by touring keyboard player Todd \u00d6gren when on the road. They are signed to [[Atlantic Records]] via [[Dave Cobb]]'s label [[Low Country Sound]], an imprint of [[Elektra Records|Elektra]].\nThey have released six albums and one EP. \n\nThe band is known for their two Grammy nominations <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/rival-sons}}</ref> , supporting [[Black Sabbath]] on [[The End Tour]], their extensive touring and their notable album release ''[[Pressure & Time]]''. .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ventsmagazine.com/2018/02/27/rival-sons-sign-low-country-sound-atlantic-records-plot-new-album/|title=Rival Sons Sign Low Country Sound Atlantic Records Plot New Album|publisher=Allmusic|date= |accessdate=2014-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2015/12/16/459972586/an-outsider-remakes-nashvilles-traditional-sound|title=An Outsider Remakes Nashville\u2019s Traditional Sound|publisher=NPR.org|date= |accessdate=2014-05-24}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and debut album ''Before The Fire'' (2006\u20132009)===\nRival Sons formed in [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] where [[Jay Buchanan]] and Michael Miley lived. Prior to the formation of Rival Sons, [[Jay Buchanan]] recorded as a solo artist and with his ''Buchanan band''. He independently released ''All Understood'' in 2004 and ''True Love EP'' in 2006. Rival Sons formed from the remnants of guitarist [[Scott Holiday]]'s previous band.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/rival-sons-mn0002672136|title=Artist Rival Sons|publisher=Allmusic|date= |accessdate=2014-05-24}}</ref> He had previously been active in a number of bands including [[Human Lab]] who were signed to [[Atlantic Records]] which he then subsequently left and formed Black Summer Crush.\n\nIn 2006 Holiday came across Buchanan while searching on [[MySpace]] for a singer. Drummer Michael Miley had previously worked with Jay (as well as having been in [[Veruca Salt]] and the [[Carson Daly]] TV show band) and he had met bassist Robin Everhart playing at a benefit concert at [[Isaac Hayes]] house for [[Hurricane Katrina]] in [[Long Beach]]. The union of these four, Holiday, Buchanan, Everhart and Miley led to the formation of Rival Sons. \n\nAs a singer-songwriter [[Jay Buchanan]] was sceptical about joining a rock and roll band but after seeing the reception to the band's debut album ''Before the Fire'' (2009) produced by [[Dave Cobb]] Jay committed to Rival Sons full-time. Jack Rivera of the [[Huffington Post]] declared them \u201cA rock band to watch\u201d in November, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeff-rivera/rock-band-to-watch-rival_b_359148.html |title=Rock Band to Watch: Rival Sons &#124; Jeff Rivera |website=Huffingtonpost.com |date=2010-03-18 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> The band, following from this acclaim, were invited to perform as a supporting act for [[AC/DC]], [[Alice Cooper]], [[Black Sabbath]] and [[Kid Rock]] shows.<ref>[http://earache.tumblr.com/post/2166446667/new-signings-rival-sons-to-support-kid-rock-at New Signings]</ref> During this time, Rival Sons also performed on the race track during a televised show of [[Indianapolis 500|The Indianapolis 500]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://rockchoice.com/riaval-sons-to-rock-indy-500 |title=Rival Sons To Rock Indy 500 |publisher=Rock Choice |date=2010-08-10 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\n=== EP, Signing and worldwide release of sophomore album ''Pressure & Time'' (2010\u20132011)===\n\nAfter the successful release of ''Before the Fire'', the band recorded a self-titled EP (independently released) in 2010, which caught the attention of [[Earache Records]] founder [[Digby Pearson]] and the band was subsequently offered a record deal in November, 2010. This signing immediately led to the band recording their notable album ''[[Pressure & Time]]'' on the Earache label in early 2011.\n\nTheir self-titled EP was re-released digitally by Earache Records in February, 2011, from which their debut European single, \u201cTorture\u201d was taken.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/01/rival-sons-self-titled-ep-out-now-on.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons Self-Titled Ep Out Now On Itunes |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-01-10 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn March, 2011 a string of shows at [[Canadian Music Week]], [[SXSW]] and the [[House of Blues]] were announced.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/03/rival-sons-announce-dates-at-canadian.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons Announce Dates At Canadian Music Week, Sxsw And The House Of Blues |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-03-04 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nRival Sons played at the [[Gene Simmons]]' \u201cAces & Angels\u201d [[Super Bowl]] party February 2, 2011<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/01/rival-sons-to-perform-at-super-bowl.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons To Perform At Super Bowl Week Kick Off Event |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-01-31 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> before making their European debut appearance at [[The Barfly|Camden Barfly]] on February 12, 2011 for the [[HMV]] Next Big Thing. The band [[Vintage Trouble]] supported their act and the show sold out in advance,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/02/rival-sons-sell-out-debut-uk-show-in.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons Sell Out Debut Uk Show In Advance |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-02-11 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> which started a nearly unbroken string of European sell-out shows.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/11/rival-sons-arrive-in-europe-for.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons Arrive In Europe For Headlining Tour |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-11-03 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nRival Sons released their second LP album in June 2011 called ''[[Pressure & Time]]'', which reached number one on Amazon's Hard Rock best sellers and nineteen on the [[Billboard Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7401032/rival-sons-new-album-hollow-bones-premiere|title=Rival Sons New Album Hollow Bones|website=Billboard|date=2016-06-09|accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/04/rival-sons-reveal-pressure-time-album.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons Reveal 'Pressure & Time' Album Cover |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-04-21 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\n[[Storm Thorgerson]] who had worked with bands such as [[Pink Floyd]], [[Led Zeppelin]] and [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], created the cover art for the album voluntarily.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.creativebloq.com/graphic-design/10-classic-storm-thorgerson-album-cover-designs-4132447|title=Ten Classic Storm Thorgerson Album Cover Designs|publisher=Creative Bloq|date= |accessdate=2018-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.digitaljournal.com/a-and-e/music/interview-with-scott-holiday-from-rival-sons/article/387675|title=Interview with Scott Holiday from Rival Sons|publisher=Digital Journal|date= |accessdate=2018-04-07}}</ref> Storm liked Rival Sons, saying about the cover art;\n\n{{quote|\"I don't think you can be certain what's going on here. To me it's a picture about fear or concern. Here's someone about to descend and doesn't know what they'll face, or where this might lead. So, in his mind he's imagining the action. That's what you see, into his mind, as he focuses on what's about to happen.\n\nWhen he gets to the bottom of the stairs, where does he go? Turn left, right or straight ahead, anything's possible. And I hope this cover will have fans of the band intrigued for a long while. To me, the cover should be part of the album, and not just packaging.\u201d\n\n- Storm Thorgerson (2011)}}\n\nRival Sons played a string of Canadian dates in May 2011, as well as [[SXSW]], Hangout festival and [[The Viper Room]], before returning to Europe to play a series of European festivals such as [[Azkena Rock Festival|Azkena]], [[Sonisphere]], [[Rock Werchter]], [[Main Square Festival|Main Square]], Putte Parken, and [[Bospop]] in July 2011. Then the band joined [[Judas Priest]], [[Queensr\u00ffche]] and [[Lady Starlight]] on tour in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/article/judas-priest-queensryche-rival-sons-live |title=Judas Priest / Queensryche / Rival Sons Live &#124; Features &#124; Clash Magazine |website=Clashmusic.com |date=2011-07-16 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nRival Sons' track \"Torture\" was featured in the film ''[[Real Steel]]'' in October 2011<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/10/rival-sons-track-featured-in-real-steel.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons Track Featured In 'Real Steel' Movie |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-10-13 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> and the band supported [[Evanescence]] by personal request of [[Amy Lee]] in the USA in October, 2011, who they would play with again in January, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/12/rival-sons-confirm-january-2012-us-tour.html |title=EARACHE NEWS: RIVAL SONS CONFIRM JANUARY 2012 U.S. TOUR WITH EVANESCENCE |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-12-15 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\nWhile Rival Sons continued to extensively tour, in 2012 they were featured on the [[Harald Schmidt Show]] as well as playing an acoustic set at the annual [[Classic Rock Roll of Honour Awards|Classic Rock awards]] located at the [[Roundhouse (venue)|Roundhouse]] in London. They were also voted \u2018Best New Band\u2019 by listeners of [[Planet Rock (radio station)|Planet Rock Radio]]. In mid 2012, ''Pressure & Time'' was voted number two album of the year and the band named \u201cBreakthrough Artist of the Year\u201d by [[Classic Rock Magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/show_interview.php?id=919|title=Rival Sons Interview|website=Classic Rock Revisited.com|date= |accessdate=2018-04-04}}</ref>\n\n===''Head Down'' and Dave Beste joins the band on bass (2012\u20132013)===\nIn February 2012 the band went into Honey Pye studios in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] for twenty days to record their third full-length LP album ''Head Down'' with [[Dave Cobb]] and this time award-winning engineer [[Vance Powell]] ([[Jack White]], [[The Raconteurs]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaudio.com/blog/vance-powell-ua-interview/ |title=Vance Powell, GRAMMY\u00ae Winner for Best Engineered Album - Blog - Universal Audio |website=Uaudio.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, the album ''Pressure & Time'' was reissued as a deluxe edition from which the last single \u201cFace of Light\u201d was taken.  A video for the single was filmed in the UK\u2019s [[peak district]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2012/04/rival-sons-face-of-light-video.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons: 'Face Of Light' Video Premieres On Vevo Front Page |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2012-04-30 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> The band then embarked on US and [[Canadian]] shows including [[Rock on the Range]] and [[Big Music Fest]] before a string of European summer festivals including [[Rock Am Ring]], [[Sweden Rock]], [[Ruisrock]], Bukta, [[Graspop]] and [[Download Festival|Download]]. The band again also played European shows with Evanescence and [[Eagles of Death Metal]] as well as [[Black Stone Cherry]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2011/11/rival-sons-confirm-2012-uk-tour-with.html |title=EARACHE NEWS: RIVAL SONS CONFIRM 2012 UK TOUR WITH BLACK STONE CHERRY |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2011-11-29 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nRival Sons third LP album ''[[Head Down (Rival Sons album)|Head Down]]'' was released in September, 2012 to critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker |first=Lee |url=http://www.metalmouth.net/2012/08/rival-sons-head-down/ |title=RIVAL SONS \u2013 Head Down |publisher=MetalMouth |date=2012-08-22 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/3v28 |title=Music - Review of Rival Sons - Head Down |publisher=BBC |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref> The album charted at number 31 in the UK album chart, number 5 in the UK indie chart, number 6 in Sweden, number 13 in Finland,  number 14 in Norway,  number 30 in Switzerland and number 38 in Germany. The debut single \u201cKeep On Swinging\u201d started a trend on Twitter, and the video was filmed in a church with snakes. The band then went on to complete another sold out European tour and were featured on the cover of [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock Magazine]]. They also the \u2018Breakthrough artist\u2019 award presented by [[Vic Reeves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/176005/9 |title=Rival Sons Win Classic Rock \"Breakthrough Artist\" Award |publisher=Stereoboard |date=2012-11-14 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn January, 2013 the band released a second single from ''Head Down'' with a video for Until The Sun Comes directed by Simon Gesrel, known for his stop-motion work and his work with Michel Gondry ([[The White Stripes]], [[Bj\u00f6rk]]).<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://earachenews.blogspot.co.uk/2013/01/rival-sons-until-sun-comes-video.html |title=Earache News: Rival Sons \"Until The Sun Comes\" Video Premieres On Vevo |website=Earachenews.blogspot.co.uk |date=2013-01-03 |accessdate=2016-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn March, 2013 the band recorded for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' The Beat and appeared on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live]]''. On March 7, 2013 Rival Sons left on a tour of Europe supported by [[The Balconies]]. In April they toured the UK supported by The Graveltones and Ulysses culminating in a sold out show at [[Shepherds Bush Empire]]. Rival Sons also played a station session in [[St. Pancras, London]] for the second time to raise money for [[NSPCC]].\n\nRival Sons did a small mid-west USA tour in May before returning to Europe in June to play more summer festivals including Download, Kivenlahti Rock, [[Bergenfest]], [[Bravalla]], Main Square and [[Open Air St. Gallen]]. The band also supported [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] in Italy and Switzerland. During this time bassist Robin Everhart quit the band for 'personal reasons' stating \"After years of intensive touring with Rival Sons, I have come to the conclusion that I am not a road-warrior and that the rock \u2019n\u2019 roll lifestyle\u2019 is not for me.\"<ref>http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/rival-sons-wish-the-best-to-departing-bassist-robin-everhart-dave-beste-will-fill-in-for-upcoming-u-s-tour-kicking-off-august-20/</ref>\n\nIn September 2013 Rival Sons supported [[Sammy Hagar]] across the US with new bassist Dave Beste, previously of [[Rocco DeLuca]] and the Burden. The band played Hard Rock Vegas in December and started the new year by headlining a street party in their hometown of [[Long Beach]].\n\n===''Great Western Valkyrie'', ''Hollow Bones'' and the [[Black Sabbath]] tour (2014\u20132017)===\n\nIn January, 2014 Rival Sons returned to the studio in Nashville with [[Dave Cobb]] to produce their fourth full-length LP album. Amidst great anticipation of their fan base, the critically acclaimed  ''[[Great Western Valkyrie]]'' was released in June, 2014. Even before the new album\u2019s release Rival Sons began their 2014 European Tour opening for [[Aerosmith]] in [[Helsinki, Finland]] and [[Stockholm, Sweden]]. The summer tour continued through Europe with club and festival dates in [[Germany]] at [[Rock Am Ring]] and [[Rock Im Park]], then onto four sold out shows in the United Kingdom and the legendary [[Isle of Wight Festival]].\n\nThey traveled back across the Atlantic to begin the USA 2014 summer tour with a sold out show at [[3rd and Lindsley]] in [[Nashville, TN]]. The US tour included several festivals and two sold out back to back dates in New York City. Rival Sons travelled back and forth between US and Canadian dates mid summer, before heading back to Northern Europe for four large festivals, ending the summer with a trip to [[South Africa]] to play the [[Oppikopi Festival]].\n\nAfter a rest Rival Sons began the second leg of the US tour playing dates in California including [[The Fillmore]] in San Francisco and a sold out show at the legendary [[The Troubadour, West Hollywood|The Troubadour]]. More Fall 2014 US Tour dates included shows in Arizona, Nebraska, Nevada, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, New York, Maryland & New Jersey.\n\nRival Sons has had several live television performances in 2014, the first on [[Le Grand Journal (Canal+)]] then in October [[Late Night with David Letterman]] and [[Later\u2026 with Jools Holland]]. They performed live at the 2014 [[Classic Rock Magazine]] [[Classic Rock Roll of Honour Awards]]. In late 2014 Rival Sons fourth LP album ''[[Great Western Valkyrie]]'' was released. It was nominated for \u201cAlbum of the Year\u201d in 2014 by Classic Rock Magazine.\n\nIn October 2015 they recorded their fifth LP album ''[[Hollow Bones]]'', again with [[music producer]] Dave Cobb, in just three weeks. Rival Sons toured the United Kingdom from March to April, 2015 as well as played the main stage at Download Festival in 2016. Their LP album ''Hollow Bones'' was officially released July 2016.\n\nAfter the recording they toured with [[Deep Purple]] in their 2016 European tour. Throughout 2016 and into early 2017 they toured as main supporting act on the entirety of [[Black Sabbath]]\u2019s notable [[The End Tour]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Rival Sons |department=Tour advertisement |magazine=[[Kerrang!]] |publicationdate=17 January 2015 |issue= 1551 |page=27}}</ref>\n\n=== Signing to [[Atlantic Records]] and ''Feral Roots'' (2018\u20132019)===\n\nOn February 27, 2018 it was officially announced that Rival Sons had signed on with [[Low Country Sound]] an imprint of [[Elektra Records|Elektra]] run by Dave Cobb.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/rival-sons-sign-to-low-country-sound-atlantic-records-tour-dates-announced-around-shaky-knees-festival-performance |title=RIVAL SONS SIGN TO LOW COUNTRY SOUND / ATLANTIC RECORDS; TOUR DATES ANNOUNCED AROUND SHAKY KNEES FESTIVAL PERFORMANCE |publisher=Bravewords |date=2018-02-18 |accessdate=2018-02-18}}</ref>\n\nRival Sons released their sixth studio album ''[[Feral Roots]]'' on January 25, 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/rival-sons-to-release-feral-roots-album-in-january/|title=RIVAL SONS To Release 'Feral Roots' Album In January|last=|first=|date=November 2, 2019|website=[[BLABBERMOUTH.NET]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 31, 2019}}</ref> to critical acclaim. The album received nominations for two awards at the [[2020 Grammy Awards]], one for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Album|Best Rock Album]] and the other for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance.]]\n\n==Artistry==\n\n===Songwriting and recording process===\n\nRival Sons early albums, including 'Pressure & Time', were written and recorded in the studio in an intense period of creativity. Speaking about the sophomore album that was written and recorded in 20 days, with producer [[Dave Cobb]], guitarist [[Scott Holiday]] states \"This is just the simplest way to not cheat ourselves or the listener, ROCK AND ROLL can't be over-thought, and if it is, it loses its immediacy and instinct...it needs to be a knife FIGHT, not a knife DANCE.\" <ref>https://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/rival-sons-reveal-new-album-details/title=Rival Sons Reveal New Album Details</ref>\n\nRival Sons have released seven records in ten years, recording regularly to deliver the immediacy needed for rock'n'roll. \"Opting to keep the sound intact and very accurate as to deliver to the listener exactly what was happening in the room when we put it down\" - [[Scott Holiday]] talking about the album ''Great Western Valkyrie''. <ref>https://loudwire.com/rival-sons-new-album-great-western-valkyre-june-release/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/in-the-studio-rival-sons-638213</ref>\n\nThe band has a long standing, friendly and professional relationship with Grammy award winning music producer [[Dave Cobb]]. Cobb has worked on all of the band's album releases and is often referred to as another member of the band. He is interested in simplicity in the recording and with the sound and vitality of real musicians in a room. <ref>https://www.soundonsound.com/people/dave-cobb</ref> Dave encourages and captures the vocal punch of the band's mainman, Jay Buchanan. \"He's unbelievable, a one-take guy \u2014 done. It's such a pleasure, because then you can get wild with things. You can experiment when it doesn't take long for the singer to do his thing.\" <ref>https://www.soundonsound.com/people/dave-cobb</ref>\n\nRival Sons recording process changed for their major label debut ''Feral Roots'', for the first time writing and recording over a process of months. Jay Buchanan stated that \"You need to shift and constantly find new soil\" within the creative process, taking eight months to write and record the Grammy nominated album instead of all their previous work which took less than six weeks. <ref>https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/rival-sons-vocalist-says-bands-writing-process-is-just-like-farming-you-need-to-shift-and-constantly-find-new-soil/</ref>\n\n===Style and influences===\n\nRival Sons are often compared to sounds of the 1970's yet they cite [[Prince]], [[D\u2019Angelo]] and [[The Roots]] as influences alongside [[Muddy Waters]] and [[Howlin\u2019 Wolf]].<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/rival-sons-interview-how-the-blues-rockers-have-forged-their-own-path-to-fame-10123483.html</ref> Jay has listed artists from [[Joni Mitchell]] to [[Sly and the Family Stone]] amongst his influences, often stating [[Van Morrison]] as one of his heroes. \"I can\u2019t overstate his influence on me as a writer and vocalist\" - Louder Sound. <ref>https://www.loudersound.com/features/jay-buchanan-the-10-records-that-changed-my-life</ref>\n\u201cIt\u2019s a modern sound,\u201d insists Holiday, \u201cbecause it\u2019s being made right now\u201d.\n\nThe band are often cited for the sartorial style as well as their musical style, with Scott Holiday known for working with tailor ''Ray Brown'' and the band often wearing boots by UK bootmaker Jeffery West. Scott Holiday is known for his slim-line tailored suits, moustache and sunglasses, Jay Buchanan's style is unpredictable including wearing flowers in his hair,<ref>https://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/176005/9</ref> flowing floral shirts and tight leather suits. <ref>https://www.menstylefashion.com/rival-sons-reinvigorating-rocknrolls-roguish-charm/</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Current members===\n* [[Jay Buchanan]] \u2013 lead vocals, harmonica, rhythm guitar <small>(2009\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Scott Holiday]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2009\u2013present)</small>\n* Mike Miley \u2013 drums, backing vocals<small>(2009\u2013present)</small>\n* Dave Beste \u2013 bass, backing vocals <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Former members===\n* Robin Everhart \u2013 bass <small>(2009\u20132013)</small>\n\n===Touring members===\n* Todd \u00d6gren \u2013 keyboards, percussion, backing vocals <small>(2014\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Timeline ===\n<!-- This is a timeline of the history of rock band Rival Sons -->\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:90 bottom:80 top:0 right:5\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/2009 till:12/31/2019\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:2009\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2009\n\nColors =\n  id:lvocals value:red           legend:Lead_Vocals\n  id:bvocals value:pink       legend:Backing_Vocals\n  id:guitar  value:green         legend:Guitar\n  id:bass    value:blue          legend:Bass\n  id:drums   value:orange        legend:Drums\n  id:harm    value:lightpurple legend:Harmonica\n  id:lines   value:black         legend:Studio_Albums\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Buchanan text:\"Jay Buchanan\"\n  bar:Holiday  text:\"Scott Holiday\"\n  bar:Everhart text:\"Robin Everhart\"\n  bar:Beste    text:\"Dave Beste\"\n  bar:Miley    text:\"Mike Miley\"\n\nPlotData =\n  width:12 textcolo